  "prompt": "Do Hindu scriptures say anything about homo sexuality?",
  "response": "Hindu scriptures address a wide range of human behaviors and ethical questions, including aspects of sexuality. However, there is no singular view on homosexuality across all Hindu texts; interpretations can vary significantly among different sects and scholars.\n\n1. **Ancient Texts**: The Manusmriti, an ancient legal text, has passages that have been interpreted to discuss sexual behavior, including mentions of same-sex relations. However, these texts often reflect the social norms and values of their times rather than universal principles.\n\n2. **Kama Sutra**: This ancient Indian text on human sexual behavior recognizes various forms of sexual expressions, including references to homosexual acts. Notably, it discusses pleasure and relationships in a broader context, considering them part of human experience.\n\n3. **Epics and Puranas**: The Mahabharata and Ramayana, along with various Puranas, have complex narratives where gender and sexuality are depicted in flexible terms. Some stories, such as those of Shikhandi in the Mahabharata, explore themes of gender fluidity and non-normative sexual orientations.\n\n4. **Modern Interpretations**: Contemporary Hindu leaders and scholars have diverse views on homosexuality. While some may reference ancient texts to support conservative views, others emphasize the principles of non-violence (ahimsa) and acceptance in Hindu ethics. \n\nOverall, the Hindu approach to sexuality, including homosexuality, is multifaceted, reflective of its vast and diverse traditions. As with any religious or philosophical system, individual interpretations and societal norms play a significant role in how these texts are understood in contemporary contexts.",
